## 2) What This System Does

### Data handling
- Loads CSV with required columns:
  - `date`, `commodity`, `price`, `temp_c`, `rainfall_mm`, `humidity_pct`
- Handles missing values via forward-fill/back-fill per commodity.
- Handles outliers via IQR clipping on `price`.
- Uses `StandardScaler` normalization for XGBoost features.

### EDA
Creates:
- time series trend chart by commodity,
- monthly seasonality chart,
- numeric correlation heatmap,
- simple volatility insights text file.

### Feature engineering
- Lag features: `price_lag1`, `price_lag7`, `price_lag30`
- Rolling means: `roll_mean_7`, `roll_mean_30`
- Seasonality: `month`, `quarter`, `dayofyear`
- Cyclic seasonality: `month_sin`, `month_cos`

### Models
- **ARIMA/SARIMAX** (implemented as ARIMAX with exogenous weather/calendar)
- **XGBoost Regressor** for supervised regression

### Evaluation
- Time-based train/test split (chronological)
- RMSE + MAE on hold-out window
- Time-series-aware cross-validation (`TimeSeriesSplit`) for XGBoost

### Prediction
- Forecast next `7`, `15`, `30` days (or custom horizons)
- Returns both XGBoost and ARIMA forecast paths
- Includes backtest overlay payload for comparison charts

## 3) Quickstart (Local)

From project root:

```bash
python -m venv .venv
```

### Windows (PowerShell)
```powershell
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
pip install -r requirements.txt
pip install -e .
```

### macOS/Linux
```bash
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
pip install -e .
```

### Step A: Prepare dataset
```bash
python scripts/generate_sample_data.py
```

### Step B: Run EDA
```bash
python scripts/generate_eda_figures.py
```

Outputs go to `notebooks/figures/`.

### Step C: Train models
```bash
python scripts/train_models.py
```

Model artifacts are saved to `models/`.

## 4) Run the FastAPI Backend

```bash
uvicorn api.main:app --reload --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8000
```

Swagger docs:
- [http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs)

### API Endpoints
- `GET /health` -> service check
- `POST /train` -> retrain ARIMA + XGBoost
- `POST /predict` -> get forecasts for selected horizons
- `GET /data` -> recent processed records
- `GET /backtest_overlay` -> actual vs model overlay payload

### Sample request
```bash
curl -X POST "http://127.0.0.1:8000/predict" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d "{\"commodity\":\"rice\",\"horizons\":[7,15,30]}"
```

## 5) Run the Streamlit Frontend

```bash
streamlit run frontend/streamlit_app.py
```

Features:
- choose commodity,
- choose forecast horizons,
- run local forecast or call FastAPI,
- visualize forecast curves,
- download forecast CSV.

## 6) Notebook Usage

Open:
- `notebooks/01_eda.ipynb`

The notebook calls `agr_forecast.eda.run_eda_plots(...)` and writes charts to `notebooks/figures/`.

## 7) Docker Deployment

### Single API container
```bash
docker build -t agri-forecast .
docker run -p 8000:8000 agri-forecast
```

The entrypoint automatically:
1. generates sample CSV,
2. trains models on first run (if artifacts are missing),
3. starts API server.

### API + Streamlit with docker compose
```bash
docker compose up --build
```

Services:
- API: [http://localhost:8000/docs](http://localhost:8000/docs)
- Streamlit: [http://localhost:8501](http://localhost:8501)

## 8) Real-World Dataset Suggestions

Replace sample CSV with real data sources:

### Commodity price data
- India Agmarknet (mandi market prices)
- FAOSTAT price databases
- World Bank commodity price datasets
- National agriculture ministry open data portals

### Weather data
- [Open-Meteo](https://open-meteo.com/) (free weather APIs)
- [NASA POWER](https://power.larc.nasa.gov/) agro-climate data
- [NOAA Climate Data Online](https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/)
- [IMD](https://mausam.imd.gov.in/) (India weather sources)

When integrating real APIs, schedule a daily ETL job that updates `data/raw/commodities.csv` before retraining.

## 9) Beginner-Friendly Workflow

1. Generate or collect CSV data.
2. Clean and preprocess with `agr_forecast.preprocess`.
3. Inspect trends/seasonality via EDA charts.
4. Build lag + rolling + seasonality features.
5. Train ARIMA and XGBoost models.
6. Evaluate with RMSE/MAE and time-aware CV.
7. Serve forecasts through FastAPI.
8. Visualize and download from Streamlit dashboard.
9. Deploy with Docker.

## 10) Notes and Limitations

- Future weather is synthesized from historical seasonal medians in demo mode.
- For production, connect to live weather forecasts for stronger accuracy.
- Forecast quality depends heavily on data quality and local market shocks.
- Retraining cadence can be daily or weekly depending on market volatility.

## 11) Verified in This Workspace

- Synthetic dataset generated (`data/raw/commodities.csv`)
- Training completed and artifacts saved (`models/*.joblib`, `models/metadata.json`)
- Local forecast function executed successfully
- FastAPI app routes loaded successfully

